Okay, from what I've read, inflation is the rate at which the general level of prices for goods and services is rising, and, subsequently, purchasing power is falling. So, if inflation is high, money doesn't buy as much as it used to.

Now, what causes inflation to rise? There are a few theories about that. One is demand-pull inflation, which happens when there's too much demand for goods and services, and not enough supply. So, if lots of people want to buy things, and there aren't enough products to go around, prices go up.

Another is cost-push inflation, where the cost of producing goods increases, maybe because raw materials are more expensive or wages have gone up. So, companies pass those costs onto consumers by raising prices.

Also, there's built-in inflation, which is when people expect prices to keep going up, so they demand higher wages, which in turn leads to higher prices for goods and services.

